explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - Macro used at function entry; macros can expand to library/helper calls (or memcmp) so its definition must be inspected to rule out any memcmp use on null-terminated strings.
memset - Standard library call present in the function; include its declaration/usage context to confirm no confused use of memory/string helpers (not directly memcmp but for completeness).
OS_TranslatePath - The function called with the input path; it is the primary place where string handling occurs and may perform string comparisons (potentially using memcmp). Its implementation must be checked.
OS_strnlen - A direct callee of OS_TranslatePath (per call graph); string-length helpers are often used alongside comparisons. Inspecting it rules out hidden memcmp usage when determining compliance.
OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch - A callee of OS_TranslatePath that may compare tokens/strings; include to check for memcmp-based string comparisons.
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - Another callee used by OS_TranslatePath that may perform token/string comparisons; must be checked.
OS_ObjectIdRelease - Included because it is part of the OS_TranslatePath call chain; any string comparisons in this chain must be ruled out.
OS_printf - Appears in the TranslatePath chain and macros; while not likely to use memcmp for comparisons, its involvement in macros/logging could hide string ops—include to be safe.
OS_FileStat_Impl - The second-level call after TranslatePath that uses the translated local_path; inspect its implementation to ensure it does not compare null-terminated strings with memcmp.
OS_TimeAssembleFromNanoseconds - Callee of OS_FileStat_Impl (per call graph); include to cover the immediate callee chain of OS_FileStat_Impl in case string comparison is delegated further.
OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN - The buffer size constant used to allocate local_path; needed to understand string-handling boundaries and whether fixed-size buffer operations could have triggered memcmp use.
OS_SUCCESS - Return-code constant used in the control flow; include to confirm control-flow paths that lead into OS_FileStat_Impl and OS_TranslatePath inspections.
int32 - The integer typedef of the function return; include so the analyst has the type definitions for completeness.
os_fstat_t - The struct/type of filestats passed into the function; include because FileStat implementations may store/compare string fields, so its definition helps trace any string comparisons.

These symbols together cover the function body, its macro expansions, and the direct callee chain where string comparisons would occur. Inspecting their definitions/implementations will determine whether memcmp is used to compare null-terminated strings and thus whether the MISRA rule is violated.
